.TH POSTCONF 5 
.SH NAME
postconf
\-
Postfix configuration parameters
.SH SYNOPSIS
.na
.nf
\fBpostconf\fR \fIparameter\fR ...

\fBpostconf -e\fR "\fIparameter=value\fR" ...
.SH DESCRIPTION
.ad
.fi
Da Postfix main.cf configuration file specifies a lil' small-ass subset
of all tha parametas dat control tha operation of tha Postfix
mail system. Parametas not specified up in main.cf is left at their
default joints.
.PP
Da general format of tha main.cf file be as bigs up:
.IP \(bu
Each logical line has tha form "parameta = value".
Whitespace round tha "=" is ignored, as is whitespace at the
end of a logical line.
.IP \(bu
Empty lines n' whitespace-only lines is ignored, as is lines
whose first non-whitespace characta be a `#'.
.IP \(bu
A logical line starts wit non-whitespace text fo' realz. A line dat starts
with whitespace continues a logical line.
.IP \(bu
A parameta value may refer ta other parameters.
.RS
.IP \(bu 
Da expressions "$name", "${name}" or "$(name)" are
recursively replaced by tha value of tha named parameter.
.IP \(bu
Da expression "${name?value}" expandz ta "value" when
"$name" is non-empty. This form is supported wit Postfix
version 2.2 n' later.
.IP \(bu
Da expression "${name:value}" expandz ta "value" when
"$name" is empty. This form is supported wit Postfix
version 2.2 n' later.
.IP \(bu
Specify "$$" ta produce a single "$" character.
.RE
.IP \(bu
When tha same parameta is defined multiple times, only tha last
instizzle is remembered.
.IP \(bu
Otherwise, tha order of main.cf parameta definitions do not matter.
.PP
Da remainder of dis document be a thugged-out description of all Postfix
configuration parameters. Default joints is shown afta tha 
parameta name up in parentheses, n' can be looked up wit the
"\fBpostconf -d\fR" command. Y'all KNOW dat shit, muthafucka! 
.PP
Note: dis aint a invitation ta make chizzlez ta Postfix
configuration parameters. Unnecessary chizzlez can impair the
operation of tha mail system.
.SH 2bounce_notice_recipient (default: postmaster)
Da recipient of undeliverable mail dat cannot be returned to
the sender n' shit.  This feature is enabled wit tha notify_classes
parameter.
.SH access_map_defer_code (default: 450)
Da numerical Postfix SMTP server response code for
an \fBaccess\fR(5) map "defer" action, includin "defer_if_permit"
or "defer_if_reject". Prior ta Postfix 2.6, tha response
is hard-coded as "450".
.PP
Do not chizzle dis unless you gotz a cold-ass lil complete understandin of RFC 5321.
.PP
This feature be available up in Postfix 2.6 n' later.
.SH access_map_reject_code (default: 554)
Da numerical Postfix SMTP server response code for
an \fBaccess\fR(5) map "reject" action.
.PP
Do not chizzle dis unless you gotz a cold-ass lil complete understandin of RFC 5321.
.SH address_verify_cache_cleanup_interval (default: 12h)
Da amount of time between \fBverify\fR(8) address verification
database cleanup runs. This feature requires dat tha database
supports tha "delete" n' "sequence" operators.  Specify a zero
interval ta disable database cleanup.
.PP
Afta each database cleanup run, tha \fBverify\fR(8) daemon logs the
number of entries dat was retained n' dropped. Y'all KNOW dat shit, muthafucka! A cleanup run is
logged as "partial" when tha daemon terminates early afta "\fBpostfix
reload\fR", "\fBpostfix stop\fR", or no requests fo' $max_idle
seconds.
.PP
Time units: s (seconds), m (minutes), h (hours), d (days), w
(weeks).
.PP
This feature be available up in Postfix 2.7.
.SH address_verify_default_transhiznit (default: $default_transport)
Overrides tha default_transhiznit parameta settin fo' address
verification probes.
.PP
This feature be available up in Postfix 2.1 n' later.
.SH address_verify_local_transhiznit (default: $local_transport)
Overrides tha local_transhiznit parameta settin fo' address
verification probes.
.PP
This feature be available up in Postfix 2.1 n' later.
.SH address_verify_map (default: peep "postconf -d" output)
Lookup table fo' persistent address verification status
storage.  Da table is maintained by tha \fBverify\fR(8) service, and
is opened before tha process releases privileges.
.PP
Da lookup table is persistent by default (Postfix 2.7 n' later).
Specify a empty table name ta keep tha shiznit up in volatile
memory which is lost afta "\fBpostfix reload\fR" or "\fBpostfix
stop\fR". This is tha default wit Postfix version 2.6 n' earlier.
.PP
Specify a location up in a gangbangin' file system dat aint gonna fill up. If the
database becomes corrupted, tha ghetto comes ta a end yo, but it ain't no stoppin cause I be still poppin'. To recover
delete (NOT: truncate) tha file n' do "\fBpostfix reload\fR".
.PP
Postfix daemon processes do not use root privileges when opening
this file (Postfix 2.5 n' later).  Da file must therefore be
stored under a Postfix-owned directory like fuckin tha data_directory.
As a migration aid, a attempt ta open tha file under a non-Postfix
directory is repimped up ta tha Postfix-owned data_directory, n' a
warnin is logged.
.PP
Examples:
.PP
.nf
.na
.ft C
address_verify_map = hash:/var/lib/postfix/verify
address_verify_map = btree:/var/lib/postfix/verify
.fi
.ad
.ft R
.PP
This feature be available up in Postfix 2.1 n' later.
.SH address_verify_negative_cache (default: yes)
Enable cachin of failed address verification probe thangs up in dis biatch.  When
this feature is enabled, tha cache may pollute quickly wit garbage.
When dis feature is disabled, Postfix will generate a address
probe fo' every last muthafuckin lookup.
.PP
This feature be available up in Postfix 2.1 n' later.
.SH address_verify_negative_expire_time (default: 3d)
Da time afta which a gangbangin' failed probe expires from tha address
verification cache.
.PP
Time units: s (seconds), m (minutes), h (hours), d (days), w (weeks).
.PP
This feature be available up in Postfix 2.1 n' later.
.SH address_verify_negative_refresh_time (default: 3h)
Da time afta which a gangbangin' failed address verification probe needz to
be refreshed.
.PP
Time units: s (seconds), m (minutes), h (hours), d (days), w (weeks).
.PP
This feature be available up in Postfix 2.1 n' later.
.SH address_verify_poll_count (default: normal: 3, overload: 1)
How tha fuck nuff times ta query tha \fBverify\fR(8) steez fo' tha completion
of a address verification request up in progress.
.PP
By default, tha Postfix SMTP server polls tha \fBverify\fR(8) service
up ta three times under non-overload conditions, n' only once when
under overload. Y'all KNOW dat shit, muthafucka!  With Postfix version 2.5 n' earlier, tha SMTP
server always polls tha \fBverify\fR(8) steez up ta three times by
default.
.PP
Specify 1 ta implement a cold-ass lil crude form of greylisting, dat is, always
defer tha straight-up original gangsta delivery request fo' a freshly smoked up address.
.PP
Examples:
.PP
.nf
.na
.ft C
# Postfix <= 2.6 default
address_verify_poll_count = 3
# Skanky manz greylisting
address_verify_poll_count = 1
.fi
.ad
.ft R
.PP
This feature be available up in Postfix 2.1 n' later.
.SH address_verify_poll_delay (default: 3s)
Da delay between queries fo' tha completion of a address
verification request up in progress.
.PP
Da default pollin delay is 3 seconds.
.PP
Time units: s (seconds), m (minutes), h (hours), d (days), w (weeks).
.PP
This feature be available up in Postfix 2.1 n' later.
.SH address_verify_positive_expire_time (default: 31d)
Da time afta which a successful probe expires from tha address
verification cache.
.PP
Time units: s (seconds), m (minutes), h (hours), d (days), w (weeks).
.PP
This feature be available up in Postfix 2.1 n' later.
.SH address_verify_positive_refresh_time (default: 7d)
Da time afta which a successful address verification probe needs
to be refreshed. Y'all KNOW dat shit, muthafucka!  Da address verification status aint updated
when tha probe fails (optimistic caching).
.PP
Time units: s (seconds), m (minutes), h (hours), d (days), w (weeks).
.PP
This feature be available up in Postfix 2.1 n' later.
.SH address_verify_relay_transhiznit (default: $relay_transport)
Overrides tha relay_transhiznit parameta settin fo' address
verification probes.
.PP
This feature be available up in Postfix 2.1 n' later.
.SH address_verify_relayhost (default: $relayhost)
Overrides tha relayhost parameta settin fo' address verification
probes. This shiznit can be overruled wit tha \fBtransport\fR(5) table.
.PP
This feature be available up in Postfix 2.1 n' later.
.SH address_verify_sender (default: $double_bounce_sender)
Da sender address ta use up in address verification probes; prior
to Postfix 2.5 tha default was "postmaster". To
avoid problems wit address probes dat is busted up in response to
address probes, tha Postfix SMTP server excludes tha probe sender
address from all SMTPD access blocks.
.PP
Specify a empty value (address_verify_sender =) or <> if you want
to use tha null sender address. Beware, some cribs reject mail from
<>, even though RFCs require dat such addresses be accepted.
.PP
Examples:
.PP
.nf
.na
.ft C
address_verify_sender = <>
address_verify_sender = postmaster@my.domain
.fi
.ad
.ft R
.PP
This feature be available up in Postfix 2.1 n' later.
.SH address_verify_sender_dependent_default_transport_maps (default: $sender_dependent_default_transport_maps)
Overrides tha sender_dependent_default_transport_maps parameter
settin fo' address verification probes.
.PP
This feature be available up in Postfix 2.7 n' later.
.SH address_verify_sender_dependent_relayhost_maps (default: $sender_dependent_relayhost_maps)
Overrides tha sender_dependent_relayhost_maps parameta settin fo' address
verification probes.
.PP
This feature be available up in Postfix 2.3 n' later.
.SH address_verify_sender_ttl (default: 0s)
Da time between chizzlez up in tha time-dependent portion of address
verification probe sender addresses. Da time-dependent portion is
appended ta tha localpart of tha address specified wit the
address_verify_sender parameter n' shit. This feature is ignored when the
probe sender addresses is tha null sender, i.e. tha address_verify_sender
value is empty or <>.
.PP
Historically, tha probe sender address was fixed. Y'all KNOW dat shit, muthafucka! This has
caused such addresses ta end up on spammer mailin lists, n' has
resulted up in wasted network n' processin resources.
.PP
To enable time-dependent probe sender addresses, specify a
non-zero time value (an integral value plus a optionizzle one-letter
suffix dat specifies tha time unit).  Specify a value of at least
several hours, ta avoid problems wit sendaz dat use greylisting.
Avoid sick TTL joints, ta make tha result less predictable.  Time
units are: s (seconds), m (minutes), h (hours), d (days), w (weeks).
.PP
This feature be available up in Postfix 2.9 n' later.
.SH address_verify_service_name (default: verify)
Da name of tha \fBverify\fR(8) address verification service. This service
maintains tha statuz of sender and/or recipient address verification
probes, n' generates probes on request by other Postfix processes.
.SH address_verify_transport_maps (default: $transport_maps)
Overrides tha transport_maps parameta settin fo' address verification
probes.
.PP
This feature be available up in Postfix 2.1 n' later.
.SH address_verify_virtual_transhiznit (default: $virtual_transport)
Overrides tha virtual_transhiznit parameta settin fo' address
verification probes.
.PP
This feature be available up in Postfix 2.1 n' later.
.SH alias_database (default: peep "postconf -d" output)
Da alias databases fo' \fBlocal\fR(8) delivery dat is updated with
"\fBnewaliases\fR" or wit "\fBsendmail -bi\fR".
.PP
This be a separate configuration parameta cuz not all the
tablez specified wit $alias_maps gotta be local files.
.PP
Examples:
.PP
.nf
.na
.ft C
alias_database = hash:/etc/aliases
alias_database = hash:/etc/mail/aliases
.fi
.ad
.ft R
.SH alias_maps (default: peep "postconf -d" output)
Da alias databases dat is used fo' \fBlocal\fR(8) delivery. Right back up in yo muthafuckin ass. See
\fBaliases\fR(5) fo' syntax details.
.PP
Da default list is system dependent.  On systems wit NIS, the
default is ta search tha local alias database, then tha NIS alias
database.
.PP
If you chizzle tha alias database, run "\fBpostalias /etc/aliases\fR"
(or wherever yo' system stores tha mail alias file), or simply
run "\fBnewaliases\fR" ta build tha necessary DBM or DB file.
.PP
Da \fBlocal\fR(8) delivery agent disallows regular expression substitution
of $1 etc. up in alias_maps, cuz dat would open a securitizzle hole.
.PP
Da \fBlocal\fR(8) delivery agent will silently ignore requests ta use
the \fBproxymap\fR(8) server within alias_maps. Instead it will open the
table directly. Before Postfix version 2.2, tha \fBlocal\fR(8) delivery
agent will terminizzle wit a gangbangin' fatal error.
.PP
Examples:
.PP
.nf
.na
.ft C
alias_maps = hash:/etc/aliases, nis:mail.aliases
alias_maps = hash:/etc/aliases
.fi
.ad
.ft R
.SH allow_mail_to_commandz (default: alias, forward)
Restrict \fBlocal\fR(8) mail delivery ta external commands.  Da default
is ta disallow delivery ta "|command" up in :include:  filez (see
\fBaliases\fR(5) fo' tha text dat defines dis terminology).
.PP
Specify zero or mo' of: \fBalias\fR, \fBforward\fR or \fBinclude\fR,
in order ta allow commandz up in \fBaliases\fR(5), .forward filez or in
:include:  files, respectively.
.PP
Example:
.PP
.nf
.na
.ft C
allow_mail_to_commandz = alias,forward,include
.fi
.ad
.ft R
.SH allow_mail_to_filez (default: alias, forward)
Restrict \fBlocal\fR(8) mail delivery ta external files. Da default is
to disallow "/file/name" destinations up in :include:  filez (see
\fBaliases\fR(5) fo' tha text dat defines dis terminology).
.PP
Specify zero or mo' of: \fBalias\fR, \fBforward\fR or \fBinclude\fR,
in order ta allow "/file/name" destinations up in \fBaliases\fR(5), .forward
filez n' up in :include:  files, respectively.
.PP
Example:
.PP
.nf
.na
.ft C
allow_mail_to_filez = alias,forward,include
.fi
.ad
.ft R
.SH allow_min_user (default: no)
Allow a sender or recipient address ta have `-' as tha first
character n' shit.  By
default, dis aint allowed, ta avoid accidents wit software that
passes email addresses via tha command line. Right back up in yo muthafuckin ass. Such software
would not be able ta distinguish a malicious address from a
bona fide command-line option. I aint talkin' bout chicken n' gravy biatch fo' realz. Although dis can be prevented by
insertin a "--" option terminator tha fuck into tha command line, dis is
hard as fuck ta enforce consistently n' globally.
.PP
Az of Postfix version 2.5, dis feature is implemented by
\fBtrivial-rewrite\fR(8).  With earlier versions dis feature was implemented
by \fBqmgr\fR(8) n' was limited ta recipient addresses only.
.SH allow_percent_hack (default: yes)
Enable tha rewritin of tha form "user%domain" ta "user@domain".
This is enabled by default.
.PP
Note: wit Postfix version 2.2, message header address rewriting
happens only when one of tha followin conditions is true:
.IP \(bu
Da message is received wit tha Postfix \fBsendmail\fR(1) command,
.IP \(bu
Da message is received from a network client dat matches
$local_header_rewrite_clients,
.IP \(bu
Da message is received from tha network, n' the
remote_header_rewrite_domain parameta specifies a non-empty value.
.br
.PP
To git tha behavior before Postfix version 2.2, specify
"local_header_rewrite_clients = static:all".
.PP
Example:
.PP
.nf
.na
.ft C
allow_percent_hack = no
.fi
.ad
.ft R
.SH allow_untrusted_routin (default: no)
Forward mail wit sender-specified routin (user[@%!]remote[@%!]site)
from untrusted clients ta destinations matchin $relay_domains.
.PP
By default, dis feature is turned off.  This closes a nasty open
relay loophole where a funky-ass backup MX host can be tricked tha fuck into forwarding
junk mail ta a primary MX host which then spams it up ta tha ghetto. Right back up in yo muthafuckin ass.
.PP
This parameta also controls if non-local addresses wit sender-specified
routin can match Postfix access tables. By default, such addresses
cannot match Postfix access tables, cuz tha address be ambiguous.
.SH alternate_config_directories (default: empty)
A list of non-default Postfix configuration directories dat may
be specified wit "-c config_directory" on tha command line, or
via tha MAIL_CONFIG environment parameter.
.PP
This list must be specified up in tha default Postfix configuration
directory, n' is used by set-gid Postfix commandz like fuckin \fBpostqueue\fR(1)
and \fBpostdrop\fR(1).
.SH always_add_missing_headaz (default: no)
Always add (Resent-) From:, To:, Date: or Message-ID: headers
when not present.  Postfix 2.6 n' lata add these headaz only
when clients match tha local_header_rewrite_clients parameter
setting.  Earlier Postfix versions always add these headers; this
may break DKIM signatures dat cover non-existent headers.
.SH always_bcc (default: empty)
Optionizzle address dat receives a "blind carbon copy" of each message
that is received by tha Postfix mail system.
.PP
Note: wit Postfix 2.3 n' lata tha BCC address be added as if it
was specified wit NOTIFY=NONE. Da sender aint gonna be notified
when tha BCC address is undeliverable, as long as all down-stream
software implements RFC 3461.
.PP
Note: wit Postfix 2.2 n' earlier tha sender is ghon be notified
when tha BCC address is undeliverable.
.PP
Note: automatic BCC recipients is produced only fo' freshly smoked up mail.
To avoid maila loops, automatic BCC recipients is not generated
afta Postfix forwardz mail internally, or afta Postfix generates
mail itself.
.SH anvil_rate_time_unit (default: 60s)
Da time unit over which client connection rates n' other rates
are calculated.
.PP
This feature is implemented by tha \fBanvil\fR(8) steez which be available
in Postfix version 2.2 n' later.
.PP
Da default interval is relatively short. Because of tha high
frequency of thugged-out shit, tha \fBanvil\fR(8) server uses volatile memory
only. Thus, shiznit is lost whenever tha process terminates.
.PP
Time units: s (seconds), m (minutes), h (hours), d (days), w (weeks).
Da default time unit is s (seconds).
.SH anvil_status_update_time (default: 600s)
How tha fuck frequently tha \fBanvil\fR(8) connection n' rate limitin server
