.SH default_delivery_slot_cost (default: 5)
How tha fuck often tha Postfix queue managerz schedula be allowed to
preempt delivery of one message wit another.
.PP
Each transhiznit maintains a so-called "available delivery slot counter"
for each message. One message can be preempted by another one when
the other message can be served up rockin no mo' delivery slots
(i.e., invocationz of delivery agents) than tha current message
counta has accumulated (or will eventually accumulate - peep about
slot loans below). This parameta controls how tha fuck often is tha counter
incremented - it happens afta each default_delivery_slot_cost
recipients done been delivered.
.PP
Da cost of 0 is used ta disable tha preemptin schedulin straight-up.
Da minimum value tha schedulin algorithm can use is 2 - use it
if you wanna maximize tha message throughput rate fo' realz. Although there
is no maximum, it don't make much sense ta use joints above say
50.
.PP
Da only reason why tha value of 2 aint tha default is tha way
this parameta affects tha delivery of mailing-list mail. In the
worst case, they delivery can take somewhere between (cost+1/cost)
and (cost/cost-1) times mo' than if tha preemptizzle schedula was
disabled. Y'all KNOW dat shit, muthafucka! Da default value of 5 turns up ta provide reasonable
message response times while makin shizzle tha mailing-list deliveries
are not extended by mo' than 20-25 cement even up in da most thugged-out shitty case.
.PP
Use \fItransport\fR_delivery_slot_cost ta specify a
transport-specific override, where \fItransport\fR is tha master.cf
name of tha message delivery transport.
.PP
