.SH default_rbl_reply (default: peep "postconf -d" output)
Da default Postfix SMTP server response template fo' a request dat is
rejected by a RBL-based restriction. I aint talkin' bout chicken n' gravy biatch. This template can be overruled
by specific entries up in tha optionizzle rbl_reply_maps lookup table.
.PP
This feature be available up in Postfix 2.0 n' later.
.PP
Da template is subject ta exactly one level of $name substitution:
.IP "\fB$client\fR"
Da client hostname n' IP address, formatted as name[address].
.br
.IP "\fB$client_address\fR"
Da client IP address.
.br
.IP "\fB$client_name\fR"
Da client hostname or "unknown". Right back up in yo muthafuckin ass. See reject_unknown_client_hostname
for mo' details.
.br
.IP "\fB$reverse_client_name\fR"
Da client hostname from address->name lookup, or "unknown".
See reject_unknown_reverse_client_hostname fo' mo' details.
.br
.IP "\fB$helo_name\fR"
Da hostname given up in HELO or EHLO command or empty string.
.br
.IP "\fB$rbl_class\fR"
Da blacklisted entitizzle type: Client host, Helo command, Sender
address, or Recipient address.
.br
.IP "\fB$rbl_code\fR"
Da numerical SMTP response code, as specified wit the
maps_rbl_reject_code configuration parameter n' shit. Note: Da numerical
SMTP response code is required, n' must step tha fuck up all up in tha start of the
reply. With Postfix version 2.3 n' lata dis shiznit may be followed
by a RFC 3463 enhanced status code.
.br
.IP "\fB$rbl_domain\fR"
Da RBL domain where $rbl_what is blacklisted.
.br
.IP "\fB$rbl_reason\fR"
Da reason why $rbl_what is blacklisted, or a empty string.
.br
.IP "\fB$rbl_what\fR"
Da entitizzle dat is blacklisted (an IP address, a hostname, a thugged-out domain
name, or a email address whose domain was blacklisted).
.br
.IP "\fB$recipient\fR"
Da recipient address or <> up in case of tha null address.
.br
.IP "\fB$recipient_domain\fR"
Da recipient domain or empty string.
.br
.IP "\fB$recipient_name\fR"
Da recipient address localpart or <> up in case of null address.
.br
.IP "\fB$sender\fR"
Da sender address or <> up in case of tha null address.
.br
.IP "\fB$sender_domain\fR"
Da sender domain or empty string.
.br
.IP "\fB$sender_name\fR"
Da sender address localpart or <> up in case of tha null address.
.br
.IP "\fB${name?text}\fR"
Expandz ta `text' if $name aint empty.
.br
.IP "\fB${name:text}\fR"
Expandz ta `text' if $name is empty.
.br
.br
.PP
Instead of $name you can also specify ${name} or $(name).
.PP
Note: when a enhanced status code is specified up in a RBL reply
template, it is subject ta modification. I aint talkin' bout chicken n' gravy biatch.  Da followin transformations
are needed when tha same RBL reply template is used fo' client,
helo, sender, or recipient access restrictions.
.IP \(bu
When rejectin a sender address, tha Postfix SMTP server
will transform a recipient DSN status (e.g., 4.1.1-4.1.6) tha fuck into the
correspondin sender DSN status, n' vice versa.
.IP \(bu
When rejectin non-address shiznit (like fuckin tha HELO
command argument or tha client hostname/address), tha Postfix SMTP
server will transform a sender or recipient DSN status tha fuck into a generic
non-address DSN status (e.g., 4.0.0).
.br
.SH default_recipient_limit (default: 20000)
Da default per-transhiznit upper limit on tha number of in-memory
recipients, n' you can put dat on yo' toast.  These limits take prioritizzle over tha global
qmgr_message_recipient_limit afta tha message has been assigned
to tha respectizzle transports, n' you can put dat on yo' toast.  See also default_extra_recipient_limit
and qmgr_message_recipient_minimum.
.PP
