.SH fallback_relay (default: empty)
Optionizzle list of relay hosts fo' SMTP destinations dat can't be
found or dat is unreachable. With Postfix 2.3 dis parameter
is renamed ta smtp_fallback_relay.
.PP
By default, mail is moonwalked back ta tha sender when a thugged-out destination is
not found, n' delivery is deferred when a thugged-out destination is unreachable.
.PP
Da fallback relays must be SMTP destinations. Right back up in yo muthafuckin ass. Specify a thugged-out domain,
host, host:port, [host]:port, [address] or [address]:port; tha form
[host] turns off MX lookups.  If you specify multiple SMTP
destinations, Postfix will try dem up in tha specified order.
.PP
Note: before Postfix 2.2, do not use tha fallback_relay feature
when relayin mail
for a funky-ass backup or primary MX domain. I aint talkin' bout chicken n' gravy biatch. Mail would loop between the
Postfix MX host n' tha fallback_relay host when tha final destination
is unavailable.
.IP \(bu
In main.cf specify "relay_transhiznit = relay",
.IP \(bu
In master.cf specify "-o fallback_relay =" (i.e., empty) at
the end of tha relay entry.
.IP \(bu
In transhiznit maps, specify "relay:\fInexthop...\fR"
as tha right-hand side fo' backup or primary MX domain entries.
.br
.PP
Postfix version 2.2 n' lata aint gonna use tha fallback_relay feature
for destinations dat it is MX host for.
