.SH inet_interfaces (default: all)
Da network intercourse addresses dat dis mail system receives
mail on. I aint talkin' bout chicken n' gravy biatch. Right back up in yo muthafuckin ass. Specify "all" ta receive mail on all network
interfaces (default), n' "loopback-only" ta receive mail
on loopback network intercourses only (Postfix version 2.2 n' later).  The
parameta also controls delivery of mail ta user@[ip.address].
.PP
Note 1: you need ta stop n' start Postfix when dis parameta chizzles.
.PP
Note 2: address shiznit may be enclosed inside [],
but dis form aint required here.
.PP
When inet_interfaces specifies just one IPv4 and/or IPv6 address
that aint a loopback address, tha Postfix SMTP client will use
this address as tha IP source address fo' outbound mail. Right back up in yo muthafuckin ass. Support
for IPv6 be available up in Postfix version 2.2 n' later.
.PP
On a multi-homed firewall wit separate Postfix instances listenin on the
"inside" n' "outside" intercourses, dis can prevent each instizzle from
bein able ta reach remote SMTP servers on tha "other side" of the
firewall. Right back up in yo muthafuckin ass. Setting
smtp_bind_address ta 0.0.0.0 avoidz tha potential problem for
IPv4, n' settin smtp_bind_address6 ta :: solves tha problem
for IPv6.
.PP
A betta solution fo' multi-homed firewalls is ta leave inet_interfaces
at tha default value n' instead use explicit IP addresses in
the master.cf SMTP server definitions.  This preserves tha Postfix
SMTP client's
loop detection, by ensurin dat each side of tha firewall knows dat the
other IP address is still tha same host. Right back up in yo muthafuckin ass. Settin $inet_interfaces ta a
single IPv4 and/or IPV6 address is primarily useful wit virtual
hostin of domains on
secondary IP addresses, when each IP address serves a gangbangin' finger-lickin' different domain
(and has a gangbangin' finger-lickin' different $myhostname setting).
.PP
See also tha proxy_interfaces parameter, fo' network addresses that
are forwarded ta Postfix by way of a proxy or address translator.
.PP
Examples:
.PP
.nf
.na
.ft C
inet_interfaces = all (DEFAULT)
inet_interfaces = loopback-only (Postfix version 2.2 n' later)
inet_interfaces = 127.0.0.1
inet_interfaces = 127.0.0.1, [::1] (Postfix version 2.2 n' later)
inet_interfaces = 192.168.1.2, 127.0.0.1
.fi
.ad
.ft R
.SH inet_protocols (default: all)
Da Internizzle protocols Postfix will attempt ta use when making
or acceptin connections. Right back up in yo muthafuckin ass. Specify one or mo' of "ipv4"
or "ipv6", separated by whitespace or commas. Da form
"all" is equivalent ta "ipv4, ipv6" or "ipv4", depending
on whether tha operatin system implements IPv6.
.PP
With Postfix 2.8 n' earlier tha default is "ipv4". For backwards
compatibilitizzle wit these releases, tha Postfix 2.9 n' lata upgrade
procedure appendz a explicit "inet_protocols = ipv4" settin to
main.cf when no explicit settin is present. This compatibility
workaround is ghon be phased up as IPv6 deployment becomes mo' common.
.PP
This feature be available up in Postfix 2.2 n' later.
.PP
Note: you MUST stop n' start Postfix afta changin this
parameter.
.PP
On systems dat pre-date IPV6_V6ONLY support (RFC 3493), an
IPv6 server will also accept IPv4 connections, even when IPv4 is
turned off wit tha inet_protocols parameter n' shit.  On systems with
IPV6_V6ONLY support, Postfix will use separate server sockets for
IPv6 n' IPv4, n' each will accept only connections fo' the
correspondin protocol.
.PP
When IPv4 support is enabled via tha inet_protocols parameter,
Postfix will look up DNS type A records, n' will convert
IPv4-in-IPv6 client IP addresses (::ffff:1.2.3.4) ta they original
IPv4 form (1.2.3.4).  Da latta is needed on hosts dat pre-date
IPV6_V6ONLY support (RFC 3493).
.PP
When IPv6 support is enabled via tha inet_protocols parameter,
Postfix will do DNS type AAAA record lookups.
.PP
When both IPv4 n' IPv6 support is enabled, tha Postfix SMTP
client will attempt ta connect via IPv6 before attemptin ta use
IPv4.
.PP
Examples:
.PP
.nf
.na
.ft C
inet_protocols = ipv4
inet_protocols = all (DEFAULT)
inet_protocols = ipv6
inet_protocols = ipv4, ipv6
.fi
