Da Postfix SMTP client time limit fo' bustin  tha SMTP RCPT TO
command, n' fo' receivin tha remote SMTP server response.
.PP
Time units: s (seconds), m (minutes), h (hours), d (days), w (weeks).
Da default time unit is s (seconds).
.SH smtp_reply_filta (default: empty)
A mechanizzle ta transform replies from remote SMTP servers one
line at a time.  This be a last-resort tool ta work round server
replies dat break inter-operabilitizzle wit tha Postfix SMTP client.
Other uses involve fault injection ta test Postfixz handlin of
invalid responses.
.PP
Notes:
.IP \(bu
In tha case of a multi-line reply, tha Postfix SMTP client
uses tha final reply linez numerical SMTP reply code n' enhanced
status code.
.IP \(bu
Da numerical SMTP reply code (XYZ) takes precedence over
the enhanced status code (X.Y.Z).  When tha enhanced status code
initial digit differs from tha SMTP reply code initial digit, or
when no enhanced status code is present, tha Postfix SMTP client
uses a generic enhanced status code (X.0.0) instead.
.br
.PP
Specify tha name of a "type:table" lookup table. Da search
strin be a single SMTP reply line as received from tha remote SMTP
server, except dat tha trailin <CR><LF> is removed.
When tha lookup succeeds, tha result replaces tha single SMTP reply
line.
.PP
Examples:
.PP
.nf
.na
.ft C
/etc/postfix/main.cf:
    smtp_reply_filta = pcre:/etc/postfix/reply_filter
.fi
.ad
.ft R
.PP
.nf
.na
.ft C
/etc/postfix/reply_filter:
    # Transform garbage tha fuck into "250-filler..." so dat it looks like
    # one line from a multi-line reply. Well shiiiit, it do not matta what tha fuck we
    # substitute here as long it has tha right syntax.  Da Postfix
    # SMTP client will use tha final linez numerical SMTP reply
    # code n' enhanced status code.
    !/^([2-5][0-9][0-9]($|[- ]))/ 250-filla fo' garbage
.fi
.ad
.ft R
.PP
This feature be available up in Postfix 2.7.
.SH smtp_rset_timeout (default: 20s)
Da Postfix SMTP client time limit fo' bustin  tha RSET command,
and fo' receivin tha remote SMTP server response. Da SMTP client
sendz RSET in
order ta finish a recipient address probe, or ta verify dat a
cached session is still usable.
.PP
This feature be available up in Postfix 2.1 n' later.
.SH smtp_sasl_auth_cache_name (default: empty)
An optionizzle table ta prevent repeated SASL authentication
failures wit tha same remote SMTP server hostname, username and
password. Y'all KNOW dat shit, muthafucka! Each table (key, value) pair gotz nuff a server name, a
username n' password, n' tha full server response. This shiznit
is stored when a remote SMTP server rejects a authentication attempt
with a 535 reply code.  As long as tha smtp_sasl_password_maps
information do no chizzle, n' as long as tha smtp_sasl_auth_cache_name
information do not expire (see smtp_sasl_auth_cache_time) the
Postfix SMTP client avoidz SASL authentication attempts wit the
same server, username n' password, n' instead bounces or defers
mail as controlled wit tha smtp_sasl_auth_soft_bounce configuration
parameter.
.PP
Use a per-destination delivery concurrency of 1 (for example,
"smtp_destination_concurrency_limit = 1",
"relay_destination_concurrency_limit = 1", etc.), otherwise multiple
delivery agents may experience a login failure all up in tha same time.
.PP
Da table must be accessed via tha proxywrite service, i.e. the
map name must start wit "proxy:". Da table should be stored under
the directory specified wit tha data_directory parameter.
.PP
This feature uses cryptographic hashin ta protect plain-text
passwords, n' requires dat Postfix is compiled wit TLS support.
.PP
Example:
.PP
.nf
.na
.ft C
smtp_sasl_auth_cache_name = proxy:btree:/var/lib/postfix/sasl_auth_cache
.fi
.ad
.ft R
.PP
This feature be available up in Postfix 2.5 n' later.
.SH smtp_sasl_auth_cache_time (default: 90d)
Da maximal age of a smtp_sasl_auth_cache_name entry before it
is removed.
.PP
This feature be available up in Postfix 2.5 n' later.
