.SH smtp_tls_exclude_ciphers (default: empty)
List of ciphers or cipher types ta exclude from tha Postfix
SMTP client cipher
list at all TLS securitizzle levels. This aint a OpenSSL cipherlist, it is
a simple list separated by whitespace and/or commas. Da elements is a
single cipher, or one or mo' "+" separated cipher properties, up in which
case only ciphers matchin \fBall\fR tha propertizzles is excluded.
.PP
Examplez (some of these will cause problems):
.sp
.in +4
.nf
.na
.ft C
smtp_tls_exclude_ciphers = aNULL
smtp_tls_exclude_ciphers = MD5, DES
smtp_tls_exclude_ciphers = DES+MD5
smtp_tls_exclude_ciphers = AES256-SHA, DES-CBC3-MD5
smtp_tls_exclude_ciphers = kEDH+aRSA
.fi
.ad
.ft R
.in -4
.PP
Da first setting, disablez anonymous ciphers. Da next setting
disablez ciphers dat use tha MD5 digest algorithm or tha (single) DES
encryption algorithm. Da next settin disablez ciphers dat use MD5 and
DES together n' shit.  Da next settin disablez tha two ciphers "AES256-SHA"
and "DES-CBC3-MD5". Da last settin disablez ciphers dat use "EDH"
key exchange wit RSA authentication.
.PP
This feature be available up in Postfix 2.3 n' later.
.SH smtp_tls_fingerprint_cert_match (default: empty)
List of aaight remote SMTP server certificate fingerprints for
the "fingerprint" TLS securitizzle level (\fBsmtp_tls_security_level\fR =
fingerprint) fo' realz. At dis securitizzle level, certificate authoritizzles is not
used, n' certificate expiration times is ignored. Y'all KNOW dat shit, muthafucka! Instead, server
certificates is verified directly via they certificate fingerprint
or hood key fingerprint (Postfix 2.9 n' later). Da fingerprint
is a message digest of tha server certificate (or hood key). The
digest algorithm is selected via tha \fBsmtp_tls_fingerprint_digest\fR
parameter.
.PP
When a \fBsmtp_tls_policy_maps\fR table entry specifies the
"fingerprint" securitizzle level, any "match" attributes up in dat entry specify
the list of valid fingerprints fo' tha correspondin destination. I aint talkin' bout chicken n' gravy biatch. Multiple
fingerprints can be combined wit a "|" delimita up in a single match
attribute, or multiple match attributes can be employed.
.PP
Example: Certificate fingerprint verification wit internal mailhub.
Two matchin fingerprints is listed. Y'all KNOW dat shit, muthafucka! This type'a shiznit happens all tha time. Da relayhost may be multiple
physical hosts behind a load-balancer, each wit its own private/public
key n' self-signed certificate fo' realz. Alternatively, a single relayhost may
be up in tha process of switchin from one set of private/hood keys to
another, n' both keys is trusted just prior ta tha transition.
.sp
.in +4
.nf
.na
.ft C
relayhost = [mailhub.example.com]
smtp_tls_security_level = fingerprint
smtp_tls_fingerprint_digest = md5
smtp_tls_fingerprint_cert_match =
    3D:95:34:51:24:66:33:B9:D2:40:99:C0:C1:17:0B:D1
    EC:3B:2D:B0:5B:B1:FB:6D:20:A3:9D:72:F6:8D:12:35
.fi
.ad
.ft R
.in -4
.PP
Example: Certificate fingerprint verification wit selected destinations.
As up in tha example above, we show two matchin fingerprints:
.sp
.in +4
.nf
.na
.ft C
/etc/postfix/main.cf:
    smtp_tls_policy_maps = hash:/etc/postfix/tls_policy
    smtp_tls_fingerprint_digest = md5
.fi
.ad
.ft R
.in -4
.sp
.in +4
.nf
.na
.ft C
/etc/postfix/tls_policy:
    example.com	fingerprint
        match=3D:95:34:51:24:66:33:B9:D2:40:99:C0:C1:17:0B:D1
        match=EC:3B:2D:B0:5B:B1:FB:6D:20:A3:9D:72:F6:8D:12:35
.fi
.ad
.ft R
.in -4
.PP
This feature be available up in Postfix 2.5 n' later.
.SH smtp_tls_fingerprint_digest (default: md5)
Da message digest algorithm used ta construct remote SMTP server
certificate fingerprints fo' realz. At tha "fingerprint" TLS securitizzle level
(\fBsmtp_tls_security_level\fR = fingerprint), tha server certificate is
verified by directly matchin its certificate fingerprint or its public
key fingerprint (Postfix 2.9 n' later). Da fingerprint is the
message digest of tha server certificate (or its hood key)
usin tha selected
algorithm. With a gangbangin' finger-lickin' digest algorithm resistant ta "second pre-image"
attacks, it aint feasible ta create a freshly smoked up hood key n' a matching
certificate (or public/private key-pair) dat has tha same ol' dirty fingerprint.
.PP
Da default algorithm is \fBmd5\fR; dis is consistent with
the backwardz compatible settin of tha digest used ta verify client
certificates up in tha SMTP server.
.PP
Da dopest practice algorithm is now \fBsha1\fR. Recent advances up in hash
function cryptanalysis have hustled ta md5 bein deprecated up in favor of sha1.
But fuck dat shiznit yo, tha word on tha street is dat as long as there be no known "second pre-image" attacks
against md5, its use up in dis context can still be considered safe.
.PP
While additionizzle digest algorithms is often available wit OpenSSL's
libcrypto, only dem used by libssl up in SSL cipher suites is available to
Postfix. For now dis means just md5 or sha1.
.PP
To find tha fingerprint of a specific certificate file, wit a
specific digest algorithm, run:
.sp
.in +4
.nf
.na
.ft C
$ openssl x509 -noout -fingerprint -\fIdigest\fR -in \fIcertfile\fR.pem
.fi
.ad
.ft R
.in -4
.PP
Da text ta tha right of "=" sign is tha desired fingerprint.
For example:
.sp
.in +4
.nf
.na
.ft C
$ openssl x509 -noout -fingerprint -sha1 -in cert.pem
SHA1 Fingerprint=D4:6A:AB:19:24:79:F8:32:BB:A6:CB:66:82:C0:8E:9B:EE:29:A8:1A
.fi
.ad
.ft R
.in -4
.PP
To extract tha hood key fingerprint from a X.509 certificate,
you need ta extract tha hood key from tha certificate n' compute
the appropriate digest of its DER (ASN.1) encoding. With OpenSSL
the "-pubkey" option of tha "x509" command extracts tha public
key always up in "PEM" format. We pipe tha result ta another OpenSSL
command dat converts tha key ta DER n' then ta tha "dgst" command
to compute tha fingerprint.
.PP
Da actual command ta transform tha key ta DER format depends
on tha version of OpenSSL used. Y'all KNOW dat shit, muthafucka! With OpenSSL 1.0.0 n' later, the
"pkey" command supports all key types. With OpenSSL 0.9.8 and
earlier, tha key type be always RSA (nobody uses DSA, n' EC
keys is not straight-up supported by 0.9.8), so tha "rsa" command is
used.
.sp
.in +4
.nf
.na
.ft C
# OpenSSL 1.0 wit all certificates n' SHA-1 fingerprints.
$ openssl x509 -in cert.pem -noout -pubkey |
    openssl pkey -pubin -outform DER |
    openssl dgst -sha1 -c
(stdin)= 64:3f:1f:f6:e5:1e:d4:2a:56:8b:fc:09:1a:61:98:b5:bc:7c:60:58
.fi
.ad
.ft R
.in -4
.sp
.in +4
.nf
.na
.ft C
# OpenSSL 0.9.8 wit RSA certificates n' MD5 fingerprints.
$ openssl x509 -in cert.pem -noout -pubkey |
    openssl rsa -pubin -outform DER |
    openssl dgst -md5 -c
(stdin)= f4:62:60:f6:12:8f:d5:8d:28:4d:13:a7:db:b2:ff:50
.fi
.ad
.ft R
.in -4
.PP
Da Postfix SMTP server n' client log tha peer (leaf) certificate
fingerprint n' hood key fingerprint when tha TLS loglevel is 2 or
higher.
.PP
\fBNote:\fR Postfix 2.9.0&ndash;2.9.5 computed tha hood key
fingerprint incorrectly. To use public-key fingerprints, upgrade
to Postfix 2.9.6 or later.
.PP
This feature be available up in Postfix 2.5 n' later.
