.SH smtp_tls_mandatory_ciphers (default: medium)
Da minimum TLS cipher grade dat tha Postfix SMTP client will
use with
mandatory TLS encryption. I aint talkin' bout chicken n' gravy biatch.  Da default value "medium" is suitable
for most destinations wit which you may wanna enforce TLS, and
is beyond tha reach of todizzlez cryptanalytic methods. Right back up in yo muthafuckin ass. See
smtp_tls_policy_maps fo' shiznit on how tha fuck ta configure ciphers
on a per-destination basis.
.PP
Da followin cipher grades is supported:
.IP "\fBexport\fR"
Enable "EXPORT" grade or betta OpenSSL
ciphers.  This is tha default fo' opportunistic encryption. I aint talkin' bout chicken n' gravy biatch. Well shiiiit, it is
not recommended fo' mandatory encryption unless you must enforce TLS
with "crippled" peers. Da underlyin cipherlist is specified via the
tls_export_cipherlist configuration parameter, which yo ass is strongly
encouraged ta not chizzle.
.br
.IP "\fBlow\fR"
Enable "LOW" grade or betta OpenSSL ciphers.  This
settin is only appropriate fo' internal mail servers.  Da underlying
cipherlist is specified via tha tls_low_cipherlist configuration
parameter, which yo ass is straight fuckin encouraged ta not chizzle.
.br
.IP "\fBmedium\fR"
Enable "MEDIUM" grade or betta OpenSSL ciphers.
Da underlyin cipherlist is specified via tha tls_medium_cipherlist
configuration parameter, which yo ass is straight fuckin encouraged ta not chizzle.
.br
.IP "\fBhigh\fR"
Enable only "HIGH" grade OpenSSL ciphers.  This settin may
be appropriate when all mandatory TLS destinations (e.g. when all
mail is routed ta a suitably capable relayhost) support at least one
"HIGH" grade cipher n' shit. Da underlyin cipherlist is specified via the
tls_high_cipherlist configuration parameter, which yo ass is strongly
encouraged ta not chizzle.
.br
.IP "\fBnull\fR"
Enable only tha "NULL" OpenSSL ciphers, these provide authentication
without encryption. I aint talkin' bout chicken n' gravy biatch.  This settin is only appropriate up in tha rare case
that all servers is prepared ta use NULL ciphers (not normally enabled
in TLS servers) fo' realz. A plausible use-case be a LMTP server listenin on a
UNIX-domain socket dat is configured ta support "NULL" ciphers. The
underlyin cipherlist is specified via tha tls_null_cipherlist
configuration parameter, which yo ass is straight fuckin encouraged ta not
change.
.br
.br
.PP
Da underlyin cipherlists fo' grades other than "null" include
anonymous ciphers yo, but these is automatically filtered up if the
Postfix SMTP client is configured ta verify server certificates.
Yo ass is straight-up unlikely ta need ta take any steps ta exclude anonymous
ciphers, they is excluded automatically as necessary.  If you must
exclude anonymous ciphers all up in tha "may" or "encrypt" securitizzle levels,
when tha Postfix SMTP client do not need or use peer certificates, set
"smtp_tls_exclude_ciphers = aNULL". To exclude anonymous ciphers only when
TLS is enforced, set "smtp_tls_mandatory_exclude_ciphers = aNULL".
.PP
This feature be available up in Postfix 2.3 n' later.
.SH smtp_tls_mandatory_exclude_ciphers (default: empty)
