.SH smtp_tls_per_site (default: empty)
Optionizzle lookup tablez wit tha Postfix SMTP client TLS usage
policy by next-hop destination n' by remote SMTP server hostname.
When both lookups succeed, tha mo' specific per-site policy (NONE,
MUST, etc) overrides tha less specific one (MAY), n' tha mo' secure
per-site policy (MUST, etc) overrides tha less secure one (NONE).
With Postfix 2.3 n' lata smtp_tls_per_site is straight fuckin discouraged:
use smtp_tls_policy_maps instead.
.PP
Use of tha bare hostname as tha per-site table lookup key is
discouraged. Y'all KNOW dat shit, muthafucka! Always use tha full destination nexthop (enclosed in
[] wit a possible ":port" suffix) fo' realz. A recipient domain or MX-enabled
transhiznit next-hop wit no port suffix may be lookin like a funky-ass bare hostname,
but is still a suitable \fIdestination\fR.
.PP
Specify a next-hop destination or server hostname on tha left-hand
side; no wildcardz is allowed. Y'all KNOW dat shit, muthafucka! Da next-hop destination is either
the recipient domain, or tha destination specified wit a \fBtransport\fR(5)
table, tha relayhost parameter, or tha relay_transhiznit parameter.
On tha right hand side specify one of tha followin keywords:
.IP "NONE"
Don't use TLS at all. This overrides a less
specific \fBMAY\fR lookup result from tha alternate host or next-hop
lookup key, n' overrides tha global smtp_use_tls, smtp_enforce_tls,
and smtp_tls_enforce_peername settings.
.br
.IP "MAY"
Try ta use TLS if tha server announces support,
otherwise use tha unencrypted connection. I aint talkin' bout chicken n' gravy biatch. This has less precedence
than a mo' specific result (includin \fBNONE\fR) from tha alternate
host or next-hop lookup key, n' has less precedence than tha more
specific global "smtp_enforce_tls = yes" or "smtp_tls_enforce_peername
= yes".
.br
.IP "MUST_NOPEERMATCH"
Require TLS encryption yo, but do not
require dat tha remote SMTP server hostname matches tha shiznit
in tha remote SMTP server certificate, or dat tha server certificate
was issued by a trusted CA. This overrides a less secure \fBNONE\fR
or a less specific \fBMAY\fR lookup result from tha alternate host
or next-hop lookup key, n' overrides tha global smtp_use_tls,
smtp_enforce_tls n' smtp_tls_enforce_peername settings.
.br
.IP "MUST"
Require TLS encryption, require dat tha remote
SMTP server hostname matches tha shiznit up in tha remote SMTP
server certificate, n' require dat tha remote SMTP server certificate
was issued by a trusted CA. This overrides a less secure \fBNONE\fR
and \fBMUST_NOPEERMATCH\fR or a less specific \fBMAY\fR lookup
result from tha alternate host or next-hop lookup key, n' overrides
the global smtp_use_tls, smtp_enforce_tls n' smtp_tls_enforce_peername
settings.
.br
.br
.PP
Da above keywordz correspond ta tha "none", "may", "encrypt" and
"verify" securitizzle levels fo' tha freshly smoked up smtp_tls_security_level parameter
introduced up in Postfix 2.3. Right back up in yo muthafuckin ass. Startin wit Postfix 2.3, n' independently
of how tha fuck tha policy is specified, tha smtp_tls_mandatory_ciphers and
smtp_tls_mandatory_protocols parametas apply when TLS encryption
is mandatory. Connections fo' which encryption is optionizzle typically
enable all "export" grade n' betta ciphers (see smtp_tls_ciphers
and smtp_tls_protocols).
.PP
As long as no secure DNS lookup mechanizzle be available, false
hostnames up in MX or CNAME responses can chizzle tha server hostname
that Postfix uses fo' TLS policy lookup n' server certificate
verification. I aint talkin' bout chicken n' gravy biatch. Even wit a slick match between tha server hostname and
the server certificate, there is no guarantee dat Postfix is connected
to tha right server n' shit.  See TLS_README (Closin a DNS loophole wit obsolete
per-site TLS policies) fo' a possible work-around.
.PP
This feature be available up in Postfix 2.2 n' later n' shit. With
Postfix 2.3 n' lata use smtp_tls_policy_maps instead.
.SH smtp_tls_policy_maps (default: empty)
Optionizzle lookup tablez wit tha Postfix SMTP client TLS security
policy by next-hop destination; when a non-empty value is specified,
this overrides tha obsolete smtp_tls_per_site parameter n' shit.  See
TLS_README fo' a mo' detailed rap of TLS securitizzle levels.
.PP
Da TLS policy table is indexed by tha full next-hop destination,
which is either tha recipient domain, or tha verbatim next-hop
specified up in tha transhiznit table, $local_transport, $virtual_transport,
$relay_transhiznit or $default_transport. This includes any enclosing
square brackets n' any non-default destination server port suffix. The
LMTP socket type prefix (inet: or unix:) aint included up in tha lookup
key.
.PP
Only tha next-hop domain, or $myhostname wit LMTP over UNIX-domain
sockets, is used as tha nexthop name fo' certificate verification. I aint talkin' bout chicken n' gravy biatch. The
port n' any enclosin square brackets is used up in tha table lookup key,
but is not used fo' server name verification.
.PP
When tha lookup key be a thugged-out domain name without enclosin square brackets
or any \fI:port\fR suffix (typically tha recipient domain), n' tha full
domain aint found up in tha table, just as wit tha \fBtransport\fR(5) table,
the parent domain startin wit a leadin "." is matched recursively. This
allows one ta specify a securitizzle policy fo' a recipient domain n' all
its sub-domains.
.PP
Da lookup result be a securitizzle level, followed by a optionizzle list
of whitespace and/or comma separated name=value attributes dat override
related main.cf settings. Da TLS securitizzle levels up in order of increasing
securitizzle are:
.IP "\fBnone\fR"
No TLS. No additionizzle attributes is supported at dis level.
.br
.IP "\fBmay\fR"
Opportunistic TLS. Right back up in yo muthafuckin ass. Since bustin  up in tha clear be acceptable,
demandin stronger than default TLS securitizzle merely reduces
inter-operability. Da optionizzle "ciphers", "exclude" n' "protocols"
attributes (available fo' opportunistic TLS wit Postfix >= 2.6)
override tha "smtp_tls_ciphers", "smtp_tls_exclude_ciphers" and
"smtp_tls_protocols" configuration parameters. When opportunistic TLS
handshakes fail, Postfix retries tha connection wit TLS disabled.
This allows mail delivery ta cribs wit non-interoperable TLS
implementations.
.br
.IP "\fBencrypt\fR"
Mandatory TLS encryption. I aint talkin' bout chicken n' gravy biatch fo' realz. At dis level
and higher, tha optionizzle "protocols" attribute overrides tha main.cf
smtp_tls_mandatory_protocols parameter, tha optionizzle "ciphers" attribute
overrides tha main.cf smtp_tls_mandatory_ciphers parameter, n' the
optionizzle "exclude" attribute (Postfix >= 2.6) overrides tha main.cf
smtp_tls_mandatory_exclude_ciphers parameter n' shit. In tha policy table,
multiple protocols or excluded ciphers must be separated by colons,
as attribute joints may not contain whitespace or commas.
.br
.IP "\fBfingerprint\fR"
Certificate fingerprint
verification. I aint talkin' bout chicken n' gravy biatch fo' realz. Available wit Postfix 2.5 n' later n' shiznit fo' realz. At dis security
level, there be no trusted certificate authorities. Put ya muthafuckin choppers up if ya feel dis! Da certificate
trust chain, expiration date, ... is not checked. Y'all KNOW dat shit, muthafucka! Instead,
the optionizzle \fBmatch\fR attribute, or else tha main.cf
\fBsmtp_tls_fingerprint_cert_match\fR parameter, lists tha certificate
fingerprints or tha hood key fingerprint (Postfix 2.9 n' later)
of tha valid server certificate. Da digest
algorithm used ta calculate tha fingerprint is selected by the
\fBsmtp_tls_fingerprint_digest\fR parameter n' shit. Multiple fingerprints can
be combined wit a "|" delimita up in a single match attribute, or multiple
match attributes can be employed. Y'all KNOW dat shit, muthafucka! Da ":" characta aint used as a
delimita as it occurs between each pair of fingerprint (hexadecimal)
digits.
.br
.IP "\fBverify\fR"
Mandatory TLS verification. I aint talkin' bout chicken n' gravy biatch.  At dis security
level, DNS MX lookups is trusted ta be secure enough, n' tha name
verified up in tha server certificate is probably obtained indirectly via
unauthenticated DNS MX lookups.  Da optionizzle "match" attribute overrides
the main.cf smtp_tls_verify_cert_match parameter n' shit. In tha policy table,
multiple match patterns n' strategies must be separated by colons.
In practice explicit control over matchin is mo' common wit the
"secure" policy, busted lyrics bout below.
.br
.IP "\fBsecure\fR"
Secure-channel TLS fo' realz. At dis securitizzle level, DNS
MX lookups, though potentially used ta determine tha muthafucka next-hop
gateway IP addresses, is \fBnot\fR trusted ta be secure enough fo' TLS
peername verification. I aint talkin' bout chicken n' gravy biatch. Instead, tha default name verified up in tha server
certificate is obtained directly from tha next-hop, or is explicitly
specified via tha optionizzle \fBmatch\fR attribute which overrides the
main.cf smtp_tls_secure_cert_match parameter n' shit. In tha policy table,
multiple match patterns n' strategies must be separated by colons.
Da match attribute is most useful when multiple domains is supported by
common server, tha policy entries fo' additionizzle domains specify matching
rulez fo' tha primary domain certificate. While transhiznit table overrides
routin tha secondary domains ta tha primary nexthop also allow secure
verification, they risk delivery ta tha wack destination when domains
change handz or is re-assigned ta freshly smoked up gateways. With tha "match"
attribute approach, routin aint perturbed, n' mail is deferred if
verification of a freshly smoked up MX host fails.
.br
.br
.PP
Example:
.PP
.nf
.na
.ft C
/etc/postfix/main.cf:
    smtp_tls_policy_maps = hash:/etc/postfix/tls_policy
    # Postfix 2.5 n' later
    smtp_tls_fingerprint_digest = md5
.fi
.ad
.ft R
.PP
.nf
.na
.ft C
/etc/postfix/tls_policy:
    example.edu                 none
    example.mil                 may
    example.gov                 encrypt protocols=TLSv1
    example.com                 verify ciphers=high
    example.net                 secure
    .example.net                secure match=.example.net:example.net
    [mail.example.org]:587      secure match=nexthop
    # Postfix 2.5 n' later
    [thumb.example.org]          fingerprint
    	match=EC:3B:2D:B0:5B:B1:FB:6D:20:A3:9D:72:F6:8D:12:35
	match=3D:95:34:51:24:66:33:B9:D2:40:99:C0:C1:17:0B:D1
.fi
.ad
.ft R
.PP
\fBNote:\fR Da \fBhostname\fR game if listed up in a non-default
settin of smtp_tls_secure_cert_match or up in tha \fBmatch\fR attribute
in tha policy table can render tha \fBsecure\fR level vulnerable to
DNS forgery. Do not use tha \fBhostname\fR game fo' secure-channel
configurations up in environments where DNS securitizzle aint assured.
.PP
This feature be available up in Postfix 2.3 n' later.
.SH smtp_tls_protocols (default: !SSLv2)
List of TLS protocols dat tha Postfix SMTP client will exclude or
include wit opportunistic TLS encryption. I aint talkin' bout chicken n' gravy biatch. Right back up in yo muthafuckin ass. Startin wit Postfix 2.6,
the Postfix SMTP client will by default not use tha obsolete SSLv2
protocol.
.PP
In main.cf tha joints is separated by whitespace, commas or
colons. In tha policy table (see smtp_tls_policy_maps) tha only valid
separator is colon. I aint talkin' bout chicken n' gravy biatch fo' realz. An empty value means allow all protocols. Da valid
protocol names, (see \\fBfBSSL_get_version\fR(3)\fR), is "SSLv2", "SSLv3"
and "TLSv1".
.PP
Note: Az of OpenSSL 1.0.1 two freshly smoked up protocols is defined, "TLSv1.1"
and "TLSv1.2". If a olda Postfix version is linked against OpenSSL
1.0.1 or later, these, or any other freshly smoked up protocol versions, are
unconditionally enabled.
.PP
To include a protocol list its name, ta exclude it, prefix tha name
with a "!" character n' shit. To exclude SSLv2 even fo' opportunistic TLS set
"smtp_tls_protocols = !SSLv2". To exclude both "SSLv2" n' "SSLv3" set
"smtp_tls_protocols = !SSLv2, !SSLv3". Explicitly listin tha protocols to
include, rather than protocols ta exclude, is supported yo, but not
recommended. Y'all KNOW dat shit, muthafucka!  Da exclusion form mo' closely matches tha behavior
when tha OpenSSL library is newer than Postfix.
.PP
Example:
.nf
.na
.ft C
