.fi
.ad
.ft R
.PP
This feature be available up in Postfix 2.6 n' later.
.SH smtp_tls_scert_verifydepth (default: 9)
Da verification depth fo' remote SMTP server certificates fo' realz. A depth
of 1 is sufficient if tha issuin CA is listed up in a local CA file.
.PP
Da default verification depth is 9 (the OpenSSL default) for
compatibilitizzle wit earlier Postfix behavior. Shiiit, dis aint no joke. Prior ta Postfix 2.5,
the default value was 5 yo, but tha limit was not straight-up enforced. Y'all KNOW dat shit, muthafucka! If
you have set dis ta a lower non-default value, certificates wit longer
trust chains may now fail ta verify. Certificate chains wit 1 or 2
CAs is common, deeper chains is mo' rare n' any number between 5
and 9 should suffice up in practice. Yo ass can chizzle a lower number if,
for example, you trust certificates directly signed by a issuin CA
but not any CAs it delegates to.
.PP
This feature be available up in Postfix 2.2 n' later.
.SH smtp_tls_secure_cert_match (default: nexthop, dot-nexthop)
How tha fuck tha Postfix SMTP client verifies tha server certificate
peername fo' the
"secure" TLS securitizzle level. In a "secure" TLS policy table
($smtp_tls_policy_maps) entry tha optionizzle "match" attribute
overrides dis main.cf setting.
.PP
This parameta specifies one or mo' patterns or strategies separated
by commas, whitespace or colons.  In tha policy table tha only valid
separator is tha colon character.
.PP
For a thugged-out description of tha pattern n' game syntax peep the
smtp_tls_verify_cert_match parameter n' shit. Da "hostname" game should
be avoided up in dis context, as up in tha absence of a secure global DNS, using
the thangs up in dis biatch of MX lookups up in certificate verification aint immune ta active
(man-in-the-middle) attacks on DNS.
.PP
