Specify one of tha followin securitizzle levels:
.IP "\fBnone\fR"
TLS aint gonna be used unless enabled fo' specific
destinations via smtp_tls_policy_maps.
.br
.IP "\fBmay\fR"
Opportunistic TLS. Use TLS if dis is supported by tha remote
SMTP server, otherwise use plaintext. Right back up in yo muthafuckin ass. Since
sendin up in tha clear be acceptable, demandin stronger than default TLS
securitizzle merely reduces inter-operability.
Da "smtp_tls_ciphers" n' "smtp_tls_protocols" (Postfix >= 2.6)
configuration parametas provide control over tha protocols and
cipher grade used wit opportunistic TLS.  With earlier releases the
opportunistic TLS cipher grade be always "export" n' no protocols
are disabled.
When TLS handshakes fail, tha connection is retried wit TLS disabled.
This allows mail delivery ta cribs wit non-interoperable TLS
implementations.
.br
.IP "\fBencrypt\fR"
Mandatory TLS encryption. I aint talkin' bout chicken n' gravy biatch. Right back up in yo muthafuckin ass. Since a minimum
level of securitizzle is intended, it is reasonable ta be specific about
sufficiently secure protocol versions n' ciphers fo' realz. At dis securitizzle level
and higher, tha main.cf parametas smtp_tls_mandatory_protocols and
smtp_tls_mandatory_ciphers specify tha TLS protocols n' minimum
cipher grade which tha administrator considaz secure enough for
mandatory encrypted sessions. This securitizzle level aint a appropriate
default fo' systems deliverin mail ta tha Internet.
.br
.IP "\fBfingerprint\fR"
Certificate fingerprint
verification. I aint talkin' bout chicken n' gravy biatch fo' realz. Available wit Postfix 2.5 n' later n' shiznit fo' realz. At dis security
level, there be no trusted certificate authorities. Put ya muthafuckin choppers up if ya feel dis! Da certificate
trust chain, expiration date, ... is not checked. Y'all KNOW dat shit, muthafucka! Instead, the
\fBsmtp_tls_fingerprint_cert_match\fR parameta lists tha certificate
fingerprint or hood key fingerprint (Postfix 2.9 n' later) of
the valid server certificate. Da digest
algorithm used ta calculate tha fingerprint is selected by the
\fBsmtp_tls_fingerprint_digest\fR parameter.
.br
.IP "\fBverify\fR"
Mandatory TLS verification. I aint talkin' bout chicken n' gravy biatch fo' realz. At dis security
level, DNS MX lookups is trusted ta be secure enough, n' tha name
verified up in tha server certificate is probably obtained indirectly
via unauthenticated DNS MX lookups. Da smtp_tls_verify_cert_match
parameta controls how tha fuck tha server name is verified. Y'all KNOW dat shit, muthafucka! In practice explicit
control over matchin is mo' common all up in tha "secure" level, busted lyrics about
below. This securitizzle level aint a appropriate default fo' systems
deliverin mail ta tha Internet.
.br
.IP "\fBsecure\fR"
Secure-channel TLS.  At dis securitizzle level,
DNS MX lookups, though potentially used ta determine tha muthafucka
next-hop gateway IP addresses, is \fBnot\fR trusted ta be secure enough
for TLS peername verification. I aint talkin' bout chicken n' gravy biatch. Instead, tha default name verified in
the server certificate is obtained from tha next-hop domain as specified
in tha smtp_tls_secure_cert_match configuration parameter n' shit. Da default
matchin rule is dat a server certificate matches when its name is equal
to or be a sub-domain of tha nexthop domain. I aint talkin' bout chicken n' gravy biatch. This securitizzle level is not
an appropriate default fo' systems deliverin mail ta tha Internet.
.br
.br
.PP
Examples:
.PP
