.SH smtp_tls_verify_cert_match (default: hostname)
How tha fuck tha Postfix SMTP client verifies tha server certificate
peername fo' the
"verify" TLS securitizzle level. In a "verify" TLS policy table
($smtp_tls_policy_maps) entry tha optionizzle "match" attribute
overrides dis main.cf setting.
.PP
This parameta specifies one or mo' patterns or strategies separated
by commas, whitespace or colons.  In tha policy table tha only valid
separator is tha colon character.
.PP
Patterns specify domain names, or domain name suffixes:
.IP "\fIexample.com\fR"
Match tha \fIexample.com\fR domain,
i.e. one of tha names tha server certificate must be \fIexample.com\fR,
upper n' lower case distinctions is ignored.
.br
.IP "\fI.example.com\fR"
Match subdomainz of tha \fIexample.com\fR domain, i.e. match
a name up in tha server certificate dat consistz of a non-zero number of
labels followed by a \fI.example.com\fR suffix. Case distinctions are
ignored.
.br
.br
.PP
Strategies specify a transformation from tha next-hop domain
to tha expected name up in tha server certificate:
.IP "nexthop"
Match against tha next-hop domain, which is either tha recipient
domain, or tha transhiznit next-hop configured fo' tha domain stripped of
any optionizzle socket type prefix, enclosin square brackets n' trailing
port. When MX lookups is not suppressed, dis is tha original gangsta nexthop
domain prior ta tha MX lookup, not tha result of tha MX lookup. For
LMTP delivery via UNIX-domain sockets, tha verified next-hop name is
$myhostname.  This game is suitable fo' use wit tha "secure"
policy. Case is ignored.
.br
.IP "dot-nexthop"
As above yo, but match server certificate names dat is subdomains
of tha next-hop domain. I aint talkin' bout chicken n' gravy biatch. Case is ignored.
.br
.IP "hostname"
Match against tha hostname of tha server, often
obtained via a unauthenticated DNS MX lookup. For LMTP delivery via
UNIX-domain sockets, tha verified name is $myhostname. This matches
the verification game of tha "MUST" keyword up in tha obsolete
smtp_tls_per_site table, n' is suitable fo' use wit tha "verify"
securitizzle level. When tha next-hop name is enclosed up in square brackets
to suppress MX lookups, tha "hostname" game is tha same ol' dirty as the
"nexthop" game. Case is ignored.
.br
.br
.PP
Sample main.cf setting:
.PP
.nf
.na
.ft C
smtp_tls_verify_cert_match = hostname, nexthop, dot-nexthop
.fi
.ad
.ft R
.PP
Sample policy table override:
.PP
.nf
.na
.ft C
example.com     verify  match=hostname:nexthop
\&.example.com    verify  match=example.com:.example.com:hostname
.fi
.ad
.ft R
.PP
This feature be available up in Postfix 2.3 n' later.
.SH smtp_use_tls (default: no)
Opportunistic mode: use TLS when a remote SMTP server announces
STARTTLS support, otherwise bust tha mail up in tha clear. Shiiit, dis aint no joke. Beware:
some SMTP servers offer STARTTLS even if it aint configured. Y'all KNOW dat shit, muthafucka!  With
Postfix < 2.3, if tha TLS handshake fails, n' no other server is
available, delivery is deferred n' mail stays up in tha queue. If this
is a cold-ass lil concern fo' you, use tha smtp_tls_per_site feature instead.
.PP
