ignored when it would override reject_unauth_destination. I aint talkin' bout chicken n' gravy biatch.  The
result is DEFER_IF_REJECT when whitelist lookup fails.  This feature
is available up in Postfix 2.8 n' later.
.br
.IP "\fBreject_rhsbl_client \fIrbl_domain=d.d.d.d\fR\fR"
Reject tha request when tha client hostname is listed wit the
A record "\fId.d.d.d\fR" under \fIrbl_domain\fR (Postfix version
2.1 n' lata only).  Each "\fId\fR" be a number, or a pattern
inside "[]" dat gotz nuff one or mo' ";"-separated numbers or
number..number ranges (Postfix version 2.8 n' later).  If no
"\fI=d.d.d.d\fR" is specified, reject tha request when tha client
hostname is listed with
any A record under \fIrbl_domain\fR. Right back up in yo muthafuckin ass. See tha reject_rbl_client
description above fo' additionizzle RBL related configuration parameters.
This feature be available up in Postfix 2.0 n' later; wit Postfix
version 2.8 n' later, reject_rhsbl_reverse_client will usually
produce betta thangs up in dis biatch.
.br
.IP "\fBpermit_rhswl_client \fIrhswl_domain=d.d.d.d\fR\fR"
Accept tha request when tha client hostname is listed wit the
A record "\fId.d.d.d\fR" under \fIrhswl_domain\fR.  Each "\fId\fR"
is a number, or a pattern inside "[]" dat gotz nuff one or more
";"-separated numbers or number..number ranges. If no
"\fI=d.d.d.d\fR" is specified, accept tha request when tha client
hostname is listed wit any A record under \fIrhswl_domain\fR.
.br
Caution: client name whitelistin is fragile, since tha client
name lookup can fail cuz of temporary outages.  Client name
whitelistin should be used only ta reduce false positives up in e.g.
DNS-based blocklists, n' not fo' makin access rule exceptions.
.br
For safety, permit_rhswl_client is silently ignored when it
would override reject_unauth_destination. I aint talkin' bout chicken n' gravy biatch.  Da result is DEFER_IF_REJECT
when whitelist lookup fails.  This feature be available up in Postfix
2.8 n' later.
.br
.IP "\fBreject_rhsbl_reverse_client \fIrbl_domain=d.d.d.d\fR\fR"
Reject tha request when tha unverified reverse client hostname
is listed wit tha A record "\fId.d.d.d\fR" under \fIrbl_domain\fR.
Each "\fId\fR" be a number, or a pattern inside "[]" dat gotz nuff
one or mo' ";"-separated numbers or number..number ranges.
If no "\fI=d.d.d.d\fR" is specified, reject tha request when the
unverified reverse client hostname is listed wit any A record under
\fIrbl_domain\fR. Right back up in yo muthafuckin ass. See tha reject_rbl_client description above for
additionizzle RBL related configuration parameters.  This feature is
available up in Postfix 2.8 n' later.
.br
.IP "\fBreject_unknown_client_hostname\fR (with Postfix < 2.3: reject_unknown_client)"
Reject tha request when 1) tha client IP address->name mapping
fails, 2) tha name->address mappin fails, or 3) tha name->address
mappin do not match tha client IP address.
.br
This be a
stronger restriction than tha reject_unknown_reverse_client_hostname
feature, which triggers only under condizzle 1) above.
.br
The
unknown_client_reject_code parameta specifies tha response code
for rejected requests (default: 450). Da reply be always 450 in
case tha address->name or name->address lookup failed due to
a temporary problem.
.br
.IP "\fBreject_unknown_reverse_client_hostname\fR"
Reject tha request when tha client IP address has no address->name
mapping.
.br
This be a weaker restriction than the
reject_unknown_client_hostname feature, which requires not only
that tha address->name n' name->address mappings exist yo, but
also dat tha two mappings reproduce tha client IP address.
.br
Da unknown_client_reject_code parameta specifies tha response
code fo' rejected requests (default: 450).  Da reply be always 450
in case tha address->name lookup failed cuz of a temporary
problem.
.br
This feature be available up in Postfix 2.3 and
later.
.br
.br
.PP
In addition, you can use any of tha following
generic restrictions.  These restrictions is applicable in
any SMTP command context.
.IP "\fBcheck_policy_service \fIservername\fR\fR"
Query tha specified policy server n' shit. Right back up in yo muthafuckin ass. See tha SMTPD_POLICY_README
document fo' details. This feature be available up in Postfix 2.1
and later.
.br
.IP "\fBdefer\fR"
Defer tha request. Da client is holla'd at ta try again n' again n' again later n' shit. This
restriction is useful all up in tha end of a restriction list, ta make
the default policy explicit.
.br
Da defer_code parameta specifies
the SMTP server reply code (default: 450).
.br
.IP "\fBdefer_if_permit\fR"
Defer tha request if some lata restriction would result up in an
explicit or implicit PERMIT action. I aint talkin' bout chicken n' gravy biatch.  This is useful when a funky-ass blacklisting
feature fails cuz of a temporary problem.  This feature be available
in Postfix version 2.1 n' later.
.br
.IP "\fBdefer_if_reject\fR"
Defer tha request if some lata restriction would result up in a
REJECT action. I aint talkin' bout chicken n' gravy biatch.  This is useful when a whitelistin feature fails
due ta a temporary problem.  This feature be available up in Postfix
version 2.1 n' later.
.br
.IP "\fBpermit\fR"
Permit tha request. This restriction is useful all up in tha end of
a restriction list, ta make tha default policy explicit.
.br
.IP "\fBreject_multi_recipient_bounce\fR"
Reject tha request when tha envelope sender is tha null address,
and tha message has multiple envelope recipients, n' you can put dat on yo' toast. This usage has
rare but legitimate applications: under certain conditions,
multi-recipient mail dat was posted wit tha DSN option NOTIFY=NEVER
may be forwarded wit tha null sender address.
.br
Note: dis restriction can only work reliably
when used up in smtpd_data_restrictions or
smtpd_end_of_data_restrictions, cuz tha total number of
recipients aint known at a earlier stage of tha SMTP conversation.
Use all up in tha RCPT stage will only reject tha second etc.  recipient.
.br
Da multi_recipient_bounce_reject_code parameta specifies the
response code fo' rejected requests (default:  550).  This feature
is available up in Postfix 2.1 n' later.
.br
.IP "\fBreject_plaintext_session\fR"
Reject tha request when tha connection aint encrypted. Y'all KNOW dat shit, muthafucka! This type'a shiznit happens all tha time. This
restriction should not be used before tha client has had a cold-ass lil chance
to negotiate encryption wit tha AUTH or STARTTLS commands.
.br
Da plaintext_reject_code parameta specifies tha response
code fo' rejected requests (default:  450).  This feature be available
in Postfix 2.3 n' later.
.br
.IP "\fBreject_unauth_pipelining\fR"
Reject tha request when tha client sendz SMTP commandz ahead
of time where it aint allowed, or when tha client sendz SMTP
commandz ahead of time without knowin dat Postfix straight-up supports
ESMTP command pipelining. This stops mail from bulk mail software
that improperly uses ESMTP command pipelinin up in order ta speed up
deliveries.
.br
With Postfix 2.6 n' later, tha SMTP server sets a per-session
flag whenever it detects illegal pipelining, includin pipelined
EHLO or HELO commands. Da reject_unauth_pipelinin feature simply
tests whether tha flag was set at any point up in time durin the
session.
.br
With olda Postfix versions, reject_unauth_pipelinin checks
the current statuz of tha input read queue, n' its usage is not
recommended up in contexts other than smtpd_data_restrictions.
.br
.IP "\fBreject\fR"
Reject tha request. This restriction is useful all up in tha end of
a restriction list, ta make tha default policy explicit.  The
reject_code configuration parameta specifies tha response code for
rejected requests (default: 554).
.br
.IP "\fBsleep \fIseconds\fR\fR"
Pause fo' tha specified number of secondz n' proceed with
the next restriction up in tha list, if any. This may stop zombie
mail when used as:
.nf
.na
.ft C
/etc/postfix/main.cf:
    smtpd_client_restrictions =
        chill 1, reject_unauth_pipelining
    smtpd_delay_reject = no
.fi
.ad
.ft R
This feature be available up in Postfix 2.3.
.br
.IP "\fBwarn_if_reject\fR"
A safety net fo' testing. When "warn_if_reject" is placed
before a reject-type restriction, access table query, or
check_policy_service query, dis logs a "reject_warning" message
instead of rejectin a request (when a reject-type restriction fails
due ta a temporary error, dis logs a "reject_warning" message for
any implicit "defer_if_permit" actions dat would normally prevent
mail from bein accepted by some lata access restriction). This
feature has no effect on defer_if_reject restrictions.
.br
.br
.PP
Other restrictions dat is valid up in dis context:
.IP \(bu
SMTP command specific restrictions dat is busted lyrics bout under
