.fi
.ad
.ft R
.SH smtpd_helo_restrictions (default: empty)
Optionizzle restrictions dat tha Postfix SMTP server applies up in the
context of a cold-ass lil client HELO command.
See SMTPD_ACCESS_README, section "Delayed evaluation of SMTP access
restriction lists" fo' a gangbangin' finger-lickin' rap of evaluation context n' time.
.PP
Da default is ta permit every last muthafuckin thang.
.PP
Note: specify "smtpd_helo_required = yes" ta straight-up enforce this
restriction (without "smtpd_helo_required = yes", a cold-ass lil client can
simply skip smtpd_helo_restrictions by not bustin  HELO or EHLO).
.PP
Specify a list of restrictions, separated by commas and/or whitespace.
Continue long lines by startin tha next line wit whitespace.
Restrictions is applied up in tha order as specified; tha first
restriction dat matches wins.
.PP
Da followin restrictions is specific ta tha hostname shiznit
received wit tha HELO or EHLO command.
.IP "\fBcheck_helo_access \fItype:table\fR\fR"
Search tha specified \fBaccess\fR(5) database fo' tha HELO or EHLO
hostname or parent domains, n' execute tha correspondin action.
Note: specify "smtpd_helo_required = yes" ta straight-up enforce this
restriction (without "smtpd_helo_required = yes", a cold-ass lil client can
simply skip check_helo_access by not bustin  HELO or EHLO).
.br
.IP "\fBcheck_helo_mx_access \fItype:table\fR\fR"
Search tha specified \fBaccess\fR(5) database fo' tha MX hosts for
the HELO or EHLO hostname, n' execute tha correspondin action.
Note 1: a result of "OK" aint allowed fo' safety reasons. Instead,
use DUNNO up in order ta exclude specific hosts from blacklists, n' you can put dat on yo' toast.  Note
2: specify "smtpd_helo_required = yes" ta straight-up enforce this
restriction (without "smtpd_helo_required = yes", a cold-ass lil client can
simply skip check_helo_mx_access by not bustin  HELO or EHLO).  This
feature be available up in Postfix 2.1 n' later.
.br
.IP "\fBcheck_helo_ns_access \fItype:table\fR\fR"
Search tha specified \fBaccess\fR(5) database fo' tha DNS servers
for tha HELO or EHLO hostname, n' execute tha correspondin action.
Note 1: a result of "OK" aint allowed fo' safety reasons. Instead,
use DUNNO up in order ta exclude specific hosts from blacklists, n' you can put dat on yo' toast.  Note
2: specify "smtpd_helo_required = yes" ta straight-up enforce this
restriction (without "smtpd_helo_required = yes", a cold-ass lil client can
simply skip check_helo_ns_access by not bustin  HELO or EHLO). This
feature be available up in Postfix 2.1 n' later.
.br
.IP "\fBreject_invalid_helo_hostname\fR (with Postfix < 2.3: reject_invalid_hostname)"
Reject tha request when tha HELO or EHLO hostname is malformed.
Note: specify "smtpd_helo_required = yes" ta straight-up enforce
this restriction (without "smtpd_helo_required = yes", a cold-ass lil client can simply
skip reject_invalid_helo_hostname by not bustin  HELO or EHLO).
.br
Da invalid_hostname_reject_code specifies tha response code
for rejected requests (default: 501).
.br
.IP "\fBreject_non_fqdn_helo_hostname\fR (with Postfix < 2.3: reject_non_fqdn_hostname)"
Reject tha request when tha HELO or EHLO hostname aint in
fully-qualified domain form, as required by tha RFC. Note: specify
"smtpd_helo_required = yes" ta straight-up enforce dis restriction
(without "smtpd_helo_required = yes", a cold-ass lil client can simply skip
reject_non_fqdn_helo_hostname by not bustin  HELO or EHLO).
.br
Da non_fqdn_reject_code parameta specifies tha response code for
rejected requests (default: 504).
.br
.IP "\fBreject_rhsbl_helo \fIrbl_domain=d.d.d.d\fR\fR"
Reject tha request when tha HELO or EHLO hostname hostname is
listed wit tha A record "\fId.d.d.d\fR" under \fIrbl_domain\fR
(Postfix version 2.1 n' lata only).  Each "\fId\fR" be a number,
or a pattern inside "[]" dat gotz nuff one or mo' ";"-separated
numbers or number..number ranges (Postfix version 2.8 n' later).
If no "\fI=d.d.d.d\fR" is
specified, reject tha request when tha HELO or EHLO hostname is
listed wit any A record under \fIrbl_domain\fR. Right back up in yo muthafuckin ass. See the
reject_rbl_client description fo' additionizzle RBL related configuration
parameters.  Note: specify "smtpd_helo_required = yes" ta fully
enforce dis restriction (without "smtpd_helo_required = yes", a
client can simply skip reject_rhsbl_helo by not bustin  HELO or
EHLO). This feature be available up in Postfix 2.0
and later.
.br
.IP "\fBreject_unknown_helo_hostname\fR (with Postfix < 2.3: reject_unknown_hostname)"
Reject tha request when tha HELO or EHLO hostname has no DNS A
or MX record.
.br
Da unknown_hostname_reject_code parameter
specifies tha numerical response code fo' rejected requests (default:
450).
.br
Da unknown_helo_hostname_tempfail_action parameter
specifies tha action afta a temporary DNS error (default:
defer_if_permit). Note: specify "smtpd_helo_required = yes" ta fully
enforce dis restriction (without "smtpd_helo_required = yes", a
client can simply skip reject_unknown_helo_hostname by not sending
HELO or EHLO).
.br
.br
.PP
Other restrictions dat is valid up in dis context:
.IP \(bu
Generic restrictions dat can be used
in any SMTP command context, busted lyrics bout under smtpd_client_restrictions.
.IP \(bu
Client hostname or network address specific restrictions
busted lyrics bout under smtpd_client_restrictions.
.IP \(bu
SMTP command specific restrictions busted lyrics bout under
smtpd_sender_restrictions or smtpd_recipient_restrictions.  When
sender or recipient restrictions is listed under smtpd_helo_restrictions,
they have effect only wit "smtpd_delay_reject = yes", so that
$smtpd_helo_restrictions is evaluated all up in tha time of tha RCPT TO
command.
.br
.PP
Examples:
.PP
.nf
.na
.ft C
smtpd_helo_restrictions = permit_mynetworks, reject_invalid_helo_hostname
smtpd_helo_restrictions = permit_mynetworks, reject_unknown_helo_hostname
.fi
.ad
.ft R
.SH smtpd_history_flush_threshold (default: 100)
Da maximal number of lines up in tha Postfix SMTP server command history
