.SH smtpd_sasl_security_options (default: noanonymous)
Postfix SMTP server SASL securitizzle options; az of Postfix 2.3
the list of available
features dependz on tha SASL server implementation dat is selected
with \fBsmtpd_sasl_type\fR.
.PP
Da followin securitizzle features is defined fo' tha \fBcyrus\fR
server SASL implementation:
.PP
Restrict what tha fuck authentication mechanizzlez tha Postfix SMTP server
will offer ta tha client.  Da list of available authentication
mechanizzlez is system dependent.
.PP
Specify zero or mo' of tha following:
.IP "\fBnoplaintext\fR"
Disallow methodz dat use plaintext passwords.
.br
.IP "\fBnoactive\fR"
Disallow methodz subject ta actizzle (non-dictionary) attack.
.br
.IP "\fBnodictionary\fR"
Disallow methodz subject ta passive (dictionary) attack.
.br
.IP "\fBnoanonymous\fR"
Disallow methodz dat allow anonymous authentication.
.br
.IP "\fBforward_secrecy\fR"
Only allow methodz dat support forward secrecy (Dovecot only).
.br
.IP "\fBmutual_auth\fR"
Only allow methodz dat provide mutual authentication (not available
with Cyrus SASL version 1).
.br
.br
.PP
By default, tha Postfix SMTP server accepts plaintext passwordz but
not anonymous logins.
.PP
Warning: it appears dat clients try authentication methodz up in the
order as advertised by tha server (e.g., PLAIN ANONYMOUS CRAM-MD5)
which means dat if you disable plaintext passwords, clients will
log up in anonymously, even when they should be able ta use CRAM-MD5.
So, if you disable plaintext logins, disable anonymous logins like a muthafucka.
Postfix treats anonymous login as no authentication.
.PP
Example:
.PP
.nf
.na
.ft C
smtpd_sasl_security_options = noanonymous, noplaintext
.fi
.ad
.ft R
