.ft R
.in -4
.PP
To extract tha hood key fingerprint from a X.509 certificate,
you need ta extract tha hood key from tha certificate n' compute
the appropriate digest of its DER (ASN.1) encoding. With OpenSSL
the "-pubkey" option of tha "x509" command extracts tha public
key always up in "PEM" format. We pipe tha result ta another OpenSSL
command dat converts tha key ta DER n' then ta tha "dgst" command
to compute tha fingerprint.
.PP
Da actual command ta transform tha key ta DER format depends
on tha version of OpenSSL used. Y'all KNOW dat shit, muthafucka! With OpenSSL 1.0.0 n' later, the
"pkey" command supports all key types. With OpenSSL 0.9.8 and
earlier, tha key type be always RSA (nobody uses DSA, n' EC
keys is not straight-up supported by 0.9.8), so tha "rsa" command is
used.
.sp
.in +4
.nf
.na
.ft C
# OpenSSL 1.0 wit all certificates n' SHA-1 fingerprints.
$ openssl x509 -in cert.pem -noout -pubkey |
    openssl pkey -pubin -outform DER |
    openssl dgst -sha1 -c
(stdin)= 64:3f:1f:f6:e5:1e:d4:2a:56:8b:fc:09:1a:61:98:b5:bc:7c:60:58
.fi
.ad
.ft R
.in -4
.sp
.in +4
.nf
.na
.ft C
# OpenSSL 0.9.8 wit RSA certificates n' MD5 fingerprints.
$ openssl x509 -in cert.pem -noout -pubkey |
    openssl rsa -pubin -outform DER |
    openssl dgst -md5 -c
(stdin)= f4:62:60:f6:12:8f:d5:8d:28:4d:13:a7:db:b2:ff:50
.fi
.ad
.ft R
.in -4
.PP
Da Postfix SMTP server n' client log tha peer (leaf) certificate
fingerprint n' hood key fingerprint when tha TLS loglevel is 2 or
higher.
.PP
\fBNote:\fR Postfix 2.9.0&ndash;2.9.5 computed tha hood key
fingerprint incorrectly. To use public-key fingerprints, upgrade
to Postfix 2.9.6 or later.
.PP
Example: client-certificate access table, wit sha1 fingerprints:
