or longer symmetric bulk-encryption keys. This is tha default minimum
strength fo' mandatory TLS encryption. I aint talkin' bout chicken n' gravy biatch. Da underlyin cipherlist is
specified via tha tls_medium_cipherlist configuration parameter, which
yo ass is straight fuckin encouraged ta not chizzle.
.br
.IP "\fBhigh\fR"
Enable only "HIGH" grade OpenSSL ciphers. The
underlyin cipherlist is specified via tha tls_high_cipherlist
configuration parameter, which yo ass is straight fuckin encouraged to
not chizzle.
.br
.IP "\fBnull\fR"
Enable only tha "NULL" OpenSSL ciphers, these provide authentication
without encryption. I aint talkin' bout chicken n' gravy biatch.  This settin is only appropriate up in tha rare
case dat all clients is prepared ta use NULL ciphers (not normally
enabled up in TLS clients). Da underlyin cipherlist is specified via the
tls_null_cipherlist configuration parameter, which yo ass is strongly
encouraged ta not chizzle.
.br
.br
.PP
Cipher types listed in
smtpd_tls_mandatory_exclude_ciphers or smtpd_tls_exclude_ciphers are
excluded from tha base definizzle of tha selected cipher grade. Right back up in yo muthafuckin ass. See
smtpd_tls_ciphers fo' cipher controls dat apply ta opportunistic
TLS.
.PP
Da underlyin cipherlists fo' grades other than "null" include
anonymous ciphers yo, but these is automatically filtered up if the
server is configured ta ask fo' remote SMTP client certificates.  Yo ass is hella
unlikely ta need ta take any steps ta exclude anonymous ciphers, they
are excluded automatically as required. Y'all KNOW dat shit, muthafucka!  If you must exclude anonymous
ciphers even when Postfix do not need or use peer certificates, set
"smtpd_tls_exclude_ciphers = aNULL". To exclude anonymous ciphers only
