.SH virtual_mailbox_domains (default: $virtual_mailbox_maps)
Postfix is final destination fo' tha specified list of domains;
mail is served up via tha $virtual_transhiznit mail delivery transport.
By default dis is tha Postfix \fBvirtual\fR(8) delivery agent.  Da SMTP
server validates recipient addresses wit $virtual_mailbox_maps
and rejects mail fo' non-existent recipients, n' you can put dat on yo' toast.  See also tha virtual
mailbox domain class up in tha ADDRESS_CLASS_README file.
.PP
This parameta expects tha same ol' dirty syntax as tha mydestination
configuration parameter.
.PP
This feature be available up in Postfix 2.0 n' later n' shit. Da default
value is backwardz compatible wit Postfix version 1.1.
.SH virtual_mailbox_limit (default: 51200000)
Da maximal size up in bytez of a individual \fBvirtual\fR(8) mailbox or
maildir file, or zero (no limit).
.PP
This parameta is specific ta tha \fBvirtual\fR(8) delivery agent.
It do not apply when mail is served up wit a gangbangin' finger-lickin' different mail
delivery program.
.SH virtual_mailbox_lock (default: peep "postconf -d" output)
How tha fuck ta lock a UNIX-style \fBvirtual\fR(8) mailbox before attempting
delivery.  For a list of available file lockin methods, use the
"\fBpostconf -l\fR" command.
.PP
This parameta is specific ta tha \fBvirtual\fR(8) delivery agent.
It do not apply when mail is served up wit a gangbangin' finger-lickin' different mail
delivery program.
.PP
This settin is ignored wit \fBmaildir\fR steez delivery, cuz
such deliveries is safe without application-level locks.
.PP
Note 1: tha \fBdotlock\fR method requires dat tha recipient UID
or GID has write access ta tha parent directory of tha recipient's
mailbox file.
.PP
Note 2: tha default settin of dis parameta is system dependent.
.SH virtual_mailbox_maps (default: empty)
Optionizzle lookup tablez wit all valid addresses up in tha domains that
match $virtual_mailbox_domains.
.PP
In a lookup table, specify a left-hand side of "@domain.tld" to
match any user up in tha specified domain dat aint gots a specific
"user@domain.tld" entry.
.PP
Da remainder of dis text is specific ta tha \fBvirtual\fR(8) delivery
agent.  It do not apply when mail is served up wit a gangbangin' finger-lickin' different
mail delivery program.
.PP
Da \fBvirtual\fR(8) delivery agent uses dis table ta look up the
per-recipient mailbox or maildir pathname.  If tha lookup result
endz up in a slash ("/"), maildir-style delivery is carried out,
otherwise tha path be assumed ta specify a UNIX-style mailbox file.
Note dat $virtual_mailbox_base is unconditionally prepended to
this path.
.PP
When a recipient address has a optionizzle address extension
(user+foo@domain.tld), tha \fBvirtual\fR(8) delivery agent looks up
the full address first, n' when tha lookup fails, it looks up the
unextended address (user@domain.tld).
.PP
Note 1: fo' securitizzle reasons, tha \fBvirtual\fR(8) delivery agent disallows
regular expression substitution of $1 etc. up in regular expression
lookup tables, cuz dat would open a securitizzle hole.
.PP
Note 2: fo' securitizzle reasons, tha \fBvirtual\fR(8) delivery agent will
silently ignore requests ta use tha \fBproxymap\fR(8) server n' shit. Instead
it will open tha table directly. Before Postfix version 2.2, the
\fBvirtual\fR(8) delivery agent will terminizzle wit a gangbangin' fatal error.
.SH virtual_maps (default: empty)
Optionizzle lookup tablez wit a) namez of domains fo' which all
addresses is aliased ta addresses up in other local or remote domains,
and b) addresses dat is aliased ta addresses up in other local or
remote domains.  Available before Postfix version 2.0. With Postfix
version 2.0 n' later, dis is replaced by separate controls: virtual_alias_domains
and virtual_alias_maps.
.SH virtual_minimum_uid (default: 100)
Da minimum user ID value dat tha \fBvirtual\fR(8) delivery agent accepts
as a result from $virtual_uid_maps table lookup.  Returned
values less than dis is ghon be rejected, n' tha message will be
deferred.
.PP
This parameta is specific ta tha \fBvirtual\fR(8) delivery agent.
It do not apply when mail is served up wit a gangbangin' finger-lickin' different mail
delivery program.
.SH virtual_transhiznit (default: virtual)
Da default mail delivery transhiznit n' next-hop destination for
final delivery ta domains listed wit $virtual_mailbox_domains.
This shiznit can be overruled wit tha \fBtransport\fR(5) table.
.PP
Specify a strang of tha form \fItransport:nexthop\fR, where \fItransport\fR
is tha name of a mail delivery transhiznit defined up in master.cf.
Da \fI:nexthop\fR destination is optional; its syntax is documented
in tha manual page of tha correspondin delivery agent.
.PP
This feature be available up in Postfix 2.0 n' later.
